    29	/**
    30	 * PR-HK-2.d — Garmin Health API connector (partner OAuth + push + backfill).
    31	 *
    32	 * Implements the PR-HK-0 {@link WearableConnector} contract. Garmin differs
    33	 * from the OAuth2 reference connectors (Oura / WHOOP / Strava) in its AUTH and
    34	 * DELIVERY model — documented inline so the divergences are explicit:
    35	 *
    36	 *  1. AUTH — Garmin uses the partner OAuth model. The legacy Health API used
    37	 *     OAuth1.0a (signed requests); the modern Health API uses OAuth2 with PKCE.
    38	 *     This connector implements the OAuth2/PKCE flow (the model Garmin steers
    39	 *     new partners to) and reads `GARMIN_CLIENT_ID` / `GARMIN_CLIENT_SECRET` /
    40	 *     `GARMIN_REDIRECT_URI` from env — never hardcoded, never logged (#1/#12).
    41	 *     The `WearableAuthModel` enum in the foundation interface is
    42	 *     (`oauth2` | `sdk-native` | `on-device`); the Garmin partner-signed push
    43	 *     is an OAuth2-family flow, so `authModel = 'oauth2'`. The partner-signed
    44	 *     PUSH delivery security is handled in the webhook controller (token +
    45	 *     fail-closed), NOT via the auth model tag.
    46	 *
    47	 *  2. DELIVERY — Garmin pushes the ACTUAL summary payload (NOT a lean
    48	 *     reference like WHOOP) to a pre-registered HTTPS callback as
    49	 *     `{ "<kind>": [ …records… ] }`. There is NO per-event HMAC signature in
    50	 *     the Garmin Health push spec, so `verifyWebhook` checks a partner-
    51	 *     configured push token (`GARMIN_PUSH_TOKEN`) delivered on the
    52	 *     `X-Garmin-Push-Token` header with a constant-time compare. If the token
    53	 *     is unconfigured the verifier FAILS CLOSED (returns false) — Garmin pushes
    54	 *     are never trusted under misconfiguration (#36 fail-loud).
    55	 *
    56	 *  3. BACKFILL — on connect Garmin supports up to a 90-day historical
    57	 *     window. We clamp to {@link DEFAULT_SINCE_DAYS} and page each summary
    58	 *     collection by ≤24h time windows (Garmin's per-request span cap),
    59	 *     bounded by {@link MAX_WINDOWS_PER_COLLECTION} so a runaway range can
    60	 *     never wedge a worker (#21 no N+1 / no runaway paging). All calls route
    61	 *     through the shared {@link ProviderHttpClient} (timeout + capped jittered
    62	 *     backoff, #35/#50).
    63	 *
    64	 * Token handoff is symmetric with PR-HK-1 / the WHOOP connector: refresh +
    65	 * access tokens are stored KMS-wrapped via {@link KmsService}; this connector
    66	 * UNWRAPS before a provider call and RE-WRAPS rotated tokens before returning
    67	 * a {@link TokenSet} (plaintext tokens never leave a method, never logged).
    68	 *
    69	 * Source (verified May 2026): Garmin Health API — Summary + Backfill + Push,
    70	 *   https://developer.garmin.com/gc-developer-program/health-api/
    71	 */
